Here's how to handle each scenario with modern MSTest (3.9+):

### 1. Windows-only → `[OSCondition]`
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[OSCondition(OperatingSystems.Windows)]
public void Registry_ReadsExpectedValue()
{
    var value = Registry.GetValue(@"HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\...", "Key", null);
    Assert.IsNotNull(value);
}
```

### 2. Skip in CI → `[CICondition]`
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[CICondition(ConditionMode.Exclude)]
public void GpuRender_ProducesExpectedOutput()
{
    var result = GpuRenderer.Render(scene);
    Assert.IsNotNull(result);
}
```

### 3. Flaky external API → `[Retry]`
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[Retry(3)]
[Timeout(10000)]
public async Task WeatherApi_ReturnsForecast()
{
    var forecast = await _weatherClient.GetForecastAsync(_testContext.CancellationToken);
    Assert.IsNotNull(forecast);
}
```

Use `[Retry]` only for genuinely flaky external dependencies — not to mask race conditions or shared-state bugs.

### 4. Temp file cleanup → `[TestCleanup]` + `IDisposable`
```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class FileProcessorTests : IDisposable
{
    private readonly TestContext _testContext;
    private readonly string _tempFile;

    public FileProcessorTests(TestContext testContext)
    {
        _testContext = testContext;
        _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public void Process_WritesExpectedOutput()
    {
        FileProcessor.Process(_tempFile);
        var content = File.ReadAllText(_tempFile);
        Assert.Contains("success", content);
    }

    // Runs even if the test fails
    public void Dispose()
    {
        if (File.Exists(_tempFile))
            File.Delete(_tempFile);
    }
}
```

`[TestCleanup]` also runs on failure and is an alternative to `IDisposable`. The cleanup order is: `[TestCleanup]` → `DisposeAsync` → `Dispose`.

### Minimum versions

| Feature | Minimum MSTest version |
|---|---|
| `[Retry]` | 3.9 |
| `[OSCondition]`, `[CICondition]` | 3.10 |
| Constructor `TestContext` injection | 3.6 |
